div.p:
                Secondly,
Some borrow of couetousnes. others that are welthie and verie wel able to liue themselues, and also to relieue others, doe of meere couetousnes borrow greate summes of monie vpon vsurie, as especially three sortes of men do, first gentlemen of greate Landes and liuings, secondly, rich fermers and yeomen, thirdly, wealthie marchants. And that because they will buie all the Lands that lies neere them, or are cōmodious for them, because the poore shall haue no place to dwel in, but by their leaue and good liking, because they wilbe richer then their fellowes, and generally because they are not cōtented with that blessed state the Lord hath set them in this life, & because they are not thankful to God that hath made thē able to liue very plentifully, and to be cōfortable and helpeful to many besides, whereas he could, and can, and sometime doeth for mens ingratitude, pull dowen vnsatiable couetous men, and setteth vp the meeke and lowlie. And I thinke these borrowers vpon vsurie sinne greatly, and that

for two causes,
